title: For Sale:  REMINGTON RAND ~ 1911A1 U.S. ARMY NEAR NEW, ALL ORIGINAL...Mfd 1944, C&R...
postcontent: Here's a very nice WWII M1911A1 U.S. Army .45 automatic pistol! Manufactured by Remington Rand in mid-1944, this pistol is completely original as shipped during World War II. All of the component parts are correct for the period of manufacture. The slide lock and 8-rib mainspring housing are of the later war serrated design. The barrel is correctly marked HS (High Standard subcontract) and is dulite blue finished. The ordnance crossed cannons cartouche, FJA acceptance stamp, P proofs, and serial number are all stamped through the finish, showing some burnishing, indicative of an original finish pistol. Likewise, the feed ramp is milled in the white. The original parkerized finish rates about 97-98% overall with only a small amount of normal handling wear. The grip straps retain virtually all of their finish and there is absolutely no rust or any pitting. The Keyes Fibre grips are correct and in excellent condition also, showing almost no wear. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is mirror bright with sharp rifling. The original finish/excellent condition "R" marked Risdon WWII contract magazines are correct as well. Remington Rand was a very innovative company, always seeking to improve manufacturing techniques. The company contributed greatly to the war effort and by war's end arguably made the highest quality 1911A1 pistol available. This is a super clean example of the best personal sidearm available during WWII. A great addition to any military collection!

This is a very scarce Walther PPK pistol that is recognized as having been issued to the dreaded Nazi Schutzstaffel, more commonly known as the "SS". The SS was a powerful paramilitary organization that was the foremost agency of surveillance and terror during the reign of Hitler's Third Reich. Subdivisions within the SS formed such groups as the Gestapo, the Waffen-SS combat troops, and the SS-Totenkopfverbande who were charged with running the extermination camps. Members of the SS were among the most ruthless of all German Nazis.

title: For Sale:  Nice Star Super B 1911style 9mm pistol w/2 magazines and cleaning rod
postcontent: This is the last of the Star Super B's that I have. Until and unless I can get more, then this is all they wrote. Like all of them, it needs a good cleaning after long term storage. They were represented to be 1949 (or thereabouts) variant of the Classic Star Model B and is marked " Modelo Super " on the right hand side of the slide. I am not sure of the year of production. This particular gun appears to be in excellent working order, and in good cosmetic condition Has a very nice vintage look. The photos are of the actual firearm and acurately depict the condition. Most notable imperfection are scratches on the frame towards the top of the trigger area. The magazines look original and seem to also be in very good condition. Grips are in excellent shape. Has the feel and weight of the old Army 1911, but somehow feels more comfortable in the hand. This model was made from 1946 to the end of classic-model production in 1983. The major change in the "Super Model " over the standard model B is the replacement of the swinging link with a Sig 210 (or modern Star) style closed cam path integral to the barrel. Related to this, a full-length guide rod with captive spring, and a quick take down lever were added as well. All of these models have a magazine safety, but one slightly different from the later S variants, and the extractor is modified to double as a loaded-chamber indicator. Additionally, the sights are improved in shape to make them easier to see, and minor changes were made to the trigger system. I had an opportunity to take one of these to the range. It is very comfortable to shoot (I.M.O. with small to medium size hands). Nice and tight groups. For a 9mm, very easy to keep on target while pumping out rounds into the bullseye. Went through about 250 round of reloads and cheap Wolf's brand. My 12 year old son had a failure to eject and a double feed, but he was limp wristing it somewhat. He is a little guy, and a 9mm is a little too much for him to handle with consistency. Except for a minor mag issue, I had no problems of any kind. One of the mags didn't feed well at first, but was an easy fix after adjusting the lips (were spread a little to far apart - not uncommon for these firearms and will not be accepted as a basis for return). Unless you are using an unconventional grip, the arch on the top part of the back basically eliminates the chance of slide or hammer bite. "Daddy" likes and kept one for myself.
